ation","justification":"The real failure is schema violations, constraint breaches, or timestamp logic errors in the database layer. Mocking the database misses these entirely. A test database (SQLite, test Postgres, or in-memory DB) is needed to verify persistence, field validation, timestamp ordering, and data integrity. LLM response content is irrelevant; we can mock the LLM and use a fixed response.","test_description":"Call the chatbot with a test question. Mock the LLM to return a fixed response; skip tone-check. Record the request timestamp. Trigger the exchange and verify the user message, response, timestamp, and metadata are persisted in the test database. Retrieve the record and verify timestamps are sequential (user_timestamp ≤ response_timestamp), fields match expectations, and all regeneration steps (if any) are logged with their own timestamps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration test with a real (or test) database is sufficient; LLM behavior is not the failure boundary here.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Second response replaces first when tone-check triggers—customer never sees draft","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is in response selection and routing logic: does the system return the regenerated response, not the rejected draft? This is orchestration that can be tested with mocked tone-check and regeneration steps. We assume those agentic steps work (mock them) and verify the response-selection logic correctly picks the final response. A real failure would be returning the wrong response variant to the customer.","test_description":"Call the chatbot and mock the initial LLM to return a response flagged as too formal by the tone-check. Mock the regeneration LLM to return a different, more casual response. Verify the customer (API caller) receives the regenerated response in the API response, not 